{
  "schema_name": "eywa_node_response",
  "schema_version": "v1",
  "orchestration_decision": "delegate",
  "decision_notes": "The problem asks for the minimum Hamming weight of the product 2023 * n. Since 2023 is not a power of 2, k(n) can potentially be small. I will decompose this into a structural analysis of the multiplier 2023 and a search for the smallest possible Hamming weight.",
  "helpers": [
    {
      "label": "structural_analyst",
      "instructions": "Analyze the number 2023 in terms of its binary properties and modular arithmetic. Specifically, investigate if there exists an n such that 2023 * n = 2^a + 2^b + ... (a sum of very few powers of 2). Determine if k(n) = 1 is possible (requires 2023 to be a power of 2, which it is not) and if k(n) = 2 is possible by checking if 2023 divides 2^a + 2^b for some a, b. Use the property that 2023 * n = 2^a + 2^b is equivalent to 2^a(2^{b-a} + 1) ≡ 0 mod 2023, or more simply, checking the order of 2 modulo the odd factors of 2023."
    },
    {
      "label": "feasibility_tester",
      "instructions": "Systematically test the feasibility of k(n) = 2 and k(n) = 3. For k(n) = 2, check if 2^a + 2^b ≡ 0 (mod 2023) for small values of a and b, or use the fact that this requires 2^{b-a} ≡ -1 (mod 2023/gcd(2023, 2^a)). For k(n) = 3, check if 2^a + 2^b + 2^c ≡ 0 (mod 2023). Provide a rigorous proof or a counter-example for the smallest candidate k(n) found."
    }
  ],
  "synthesis_brief": "Combine the structural findings (the impossibility of k(n)=1) with the feasibility results (the smallest k(n) found through modular testing) to conclude the minimum value of k(n)."
}
```

